aVPhotos: Popole Misenga was one of the faces of the Rio 2016 Olympics, as part of the Games' first refugee team. Hide Caption 1 of 10\u000a\u000aPhotos: The Olympics brought Misenga global attention and contact with the likes of IOC president Thomas Bach. Hide Caption 2 of 10\u000a\u000aPhotos: Misenga's goal was to win a medal in Rio and he triumphed in his opening bout against India's Avtar Singh. Hide Caption 3 of 10\u000a\u000aPhotos: But he was eventually eliminated by world No. 1 Gwak Dong-han, who knocked him out at the end of the four-minute contest. Hide Caption 4 of 10\u000a\u000aPhotos: Misenga previously competed for Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) but ran away from the country's team base during the 2013 World Championships in Rio. Hide Caption 5 of 10\u000a\u000aPhotos: Yolande Mabika (right) and Misenga at the Rio Olympics in 2016. Three years earlier, Mabika, also a former DRC athlete, helped Misenga escape the team's Rio base. Hide Caption 6 of 10\u000a\u000aPhotos: Orphaned at the age of nine, it was an emotional Olympics for Misenga who had not seen many of his family members for more than a decade. Hide Caption 7 of 10\u000a\u000aPhotos: Misenga now has a new family in Rio, living in one of the city's many favelas with his Brazilian partner and their children. Hide Caption 8 of 10\u000a\u000aPhotos: The 25-year-old describes his current existence as "a good life" and has his sights set on the next Olympics in Tokyo. Hide Caption 9 of 10
