aVOCALA, Fla. - A 53-year-old man was arrested Thursday on suspicion of trying to use his prosthetic leg to smuggle heroin into the Marion County Jail.\u000a\u000a[RECOMMENDED: Suspected car thief arrested while viewing solar eclipse, deputies say | Anonymous letter calls home 'trash dump;' community helps clean up]\u000a\u000aWilliam Conley, of Alabama, was arrested on charges of use or possession of drug paraphernalia and smuggling contraband into a detention facility.\u000a\u000aAccording to the Marion County Sheriff's Office, Sumter County deputies took Conley to the Marion County Jail, where he was searched.\u000a\u000aDetention deputies ordered Conley to remove his fake leg, but he was hesitant and asked if that was necessary, officials said.\u000a\u000aConley then complied and deputies found a syringe inside his prosthetic leg, according to authorities.\u000a\u000a[SEE THESE? Break-ing news: TV mistakes | Tattoo spell check | World's craziest beach]\u000a\u000aConley said he used the syringe to inject chickens with vitamins, but field tests showed that a liquid inside the syringe tested positive for heroin, according to authorities.\u000a\u000aConley said he used methamphetamine and morphine but insisted that the needle was not used for heroin, deputies said.\u000a\u000aHe was arrested, and the syringe was placed into evidence.\u000a\u000aConley was initially taken to jail on a warrant for a charge of failure to appear in court for a driving with suspended license charge.\u000a\u000aCopyright 2017 by WKMG ClickOrlando - All rights reserved.
