aVWATERFORD, Mich. (WXYZ) - A listing for a mansion in Waterford, Michigan is going viral. The home sits on a lake, but the inside of the home is what has people talking.\u000a\u000aPHOTOS | Check out all the pictures from the listing for the mansion\u000a\u000aMark Z, the realtor selling the mansion, said he was taken aback when he first walked in.\u000a\u000a"I was shocked that the decor has not been updated from back in time when this was the style," he said.\u000a\u000aThat time is the 1990s.\u000a\u000a"I feel like I went back in time," said realtor Mark Z. "The colors are unique. The decor is unique."\u000a\u000aHe isn't surprised the listing is starting to go viral.\u000a\u000aThe house on Forest Bay Drive boasts more than 10,000 square feet, six bedrooms, eight bathrooms and a million dollar lake view.\u000a\u000aThe various shades of pink, purple and turquoise travel from room to room.\u000a\u000aIt's on sale for approximately $800,000, although it was appraised for $1.8 million.\u000a\u000a"It's definitely going to be a harder sell because of the uniqueness of the colors and the decor," Mark Z said.\u000a\u000aThe mansion also has features like a home theater and an indoor in-ground pool in the lower level\u000a\u000aMark Z says it could cost anywhere from $500,000 to a million dollars to update the inside of the house.\u000a\u000a"For remodeling, they say anywhere from $50-$100 a square foot, I think you could recoup maybe 25 percent of that," he said.\u000a\u000aHe has a guarantee to sell a home or he will buy it, but this is a short sale, so that could be tricky.\u000a\u000a"We would definitely purchase it for the price that we are listing it at, but in this case, like I said, we need the bank to approve it, so it kind of ties our hands."\u000a\u000aHowever, he believes a buyer is out there.
p649
aV(CNN) Two trains collided in Alexandria on Friday, leaving 41 dead and 179 others injured, Egypt's Health Ministry said.\u000a\u000aThe collision involved one train traveling from Cairo and another from Port Said, according to state news agency Al-Ahram.\u000a\u000aPresident Abdel Fattah el-Sisi issued a statement offering his condolences to the families of the victims.\u000a\u000aGeneral Prosecutor Nabeel Ahmed dispatched a team from his office in Alexandria to the collision site to run the inspection, transport the dead to the nearest hospitals, release the victims to their families after the identification process is completed, and gather accounts from the wounded.\u000a\u000aIn addition, an engineering team will be dispatched to the scene to examine the causes of the accident and determine the party responsible.\u000a\u000aRead More
