aVOREGON CITY, Ore. \u2013 Officers and emergency personnel recovered the body of a climber from a rock climbing area in Oregon City.\u000a\u000aThe climber was killed by falling rock at the edge of Waterboard Park, officials at the scene said.\u000a\u000aSomeone reported the climber missing on Wednesday night. A friend of the climber found his car near the park, and later found him unconscious at a "known climbing area."\u000a\u000aEmergency crews said they found the victim suspended on an unstable rock wall about 30 feet from the ground. He was pronounced deceased at the scene.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aHis name has not been released, but Clackamas Fire officials say he was from Canby.\u000a\u000a"It was obvious that a large amount of rock had fallen from above the climber and presumed to be the cause of injury to the climber," a Clackamas Fire Dist. No. 1 official said. "In recovery mode crews will develop multiple plans and safely and methodically remove victims from the situation."\u000a\u000aOfficials said they weren't sure whether the climber was wearing a helmet. They think the rock that hit him was about 3 feet wide and 10 feet long.\u000a\u000aThe road around the park was closed a few years ago because of the falling rocks and unstable hillside. Still, families like Angela Woods' come to the park to scamper around on the boulders.\u000a\u000aWoods admit she's a little nervous watching her 7-year-old daughter climb like a pro.\u000a\u000a"it's a little unnerving, yes." said Woods. "But she's been up here since she was practically a baby, so she knows her way around. You just always have to be aware of your surroundings."\u000a\u000aA Clackamas Fire spokesperson said the tough territory made the recovery of the climber difficult and dangerous, but no rescue personnel were injured.\u000a\u000aWith unstable conditions and remote access to the park, officials said they strongly recommend that people do not climb in the park area.\u000a\u000aThe National Parks Service has a list of safety warnings for rock climbers:
